children.subject:
I took math 136 spring 2018. Spiritually the class is definitely related to CS70 and CS170. But material-wise there is almost no overlap with 170. It does overlap with CS 70, but 70 barely covers imcompleteness and undecidability. 136 goes into this concept in much much more depth, and I finally felt like I understood it after taking 136.

Never took 172, but surely it will overlap almost entirely with the computability portion of CS172, and almost none of the complexity portion.

I'll also mention that my 136 (I'm sure it depends on the professor) covered some mathematical logic near the end, hence the incompleteness part.  We proved Gödel's Incompleteness Theorems and quite a bit of other stuff regarding provability, satisfiability, and truth, and went through the basics of the language used by logicians.  I don't know how much 172 covers these topics since they're not really focused on computability.

history.content: How much overlap is there between Math 136 (Incompleteness and Undecidability) and CS70, CS170, and CS172?
history.subject: Math 136 amount of overlap with CS theory curriculum
